      <h4>Request Phase</h4>
      <p>In this phase, the <b>Feature Requester</b> submits their feature idea to the open-source project or the Open Source 
      Firmware Foundation (OSFF). Together, the requester and the community create a <b>Feature Design Document</b> that outlines
      the scope, timeline, and design of the feature.</p>
      <h4>Implementation Phase</h4>
      <p>After the feature request is approved, the <b>Implementation Team</b> takes over. This team, formed from the community, 
      OSFF, or the feature requester, develops the feature following the agreed-upon design. The focus is on ensuring code 
      quality, testing, and alignment with the overall project goals.</p>
      <h4>Finalization Phase</h4>
      <p>The final step is ensuring the feature is ready for upstream integration and is well-documented. If the feature was 
      developed upstream from the start, this phase is simpler. Otherwise, the code is reviewed by the community before 
      it becomes part of the project.</p>

      <h3>How to Get Started</h3>
      <p>If you're interested in requesting a feature for an open-source project or have questions about the process,
      the Open Source Firmware Foundation (OSFF) is here to help. We can facilitate discussions and ensure a smooth
      workflow between all parties involved. Reach out to us via <a href="mailto:feature-request@osfw.foundation" 
      class="inline-link color-primary">feature-request@osfw.foundation</a>.</p>

